<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">40712663</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>08</Month><Day>26</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>08</Month><Day>26</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Electronic-Print"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1555-0273</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>20</Volume><Issue>9</Issue><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Sep</Month><Day>01</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>International journal of sports physiology and performance</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Int J Sports Physiol Perform</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Perceptual, Thermoregulatory, and Performance Effects of Menthol Gel Application in Trained Triathletes Exercising in Hot Conditions.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>1271</StartPage><EndPage>1277</EndPage><MedlinePgn>1271-1277</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1123/ijspp.2025-0038</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="PURPOSE" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">Topical menthol application improves thermal perception and enhances performance but reduces sweat production in hot environments. In the aquatic environment, where sweat evaporation is of limited thermoregulatory benefit (ie,&#xa0;minimal evaporation) and leads to dehydration and cardiovascular strain, downregulating thermoregulatory sweating may have little consequence. However, it may preserve hydration status and improve subsequent performance, especially in air (ie,&#xa0;after first transition in triathlon); we tested this hypothesis.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHOD" NlmCategory="METHODS">Eight trained triathletes (age 36 [5]&#xa0;y; height 1.77 [0.1]&#xa0;m; mass 73.9 [8.0]&#xa0;kg) completed 2 experimental conditions with prior whole-body application of menthol GEL (40&#xa0;g, 3.5% menthol) contrasted to NO-GEL. The protocol comprised 30 minutes of&#xa0;swimming (at 85% of&#xa0;400-m personal best) in tropical water (29 &#xb0;C) followed by a 20-km self-paced cycling time trial. Measures were deep body temperature (gastrointestinal pill), skin temperature, sweat production, rating of perceived exertion, thermal sensation, and thermal comfort. Paired t test and analysis of variance compared the data (.05 alpha level).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Wet-bulb globe temperature equated to "red flag" conditions-heat-injury potential for all participants. Terminal gastrointestinal temperature was 38.8 &#xb0;C (0.3 &#xb0;C) and 38.8 &#xb0;C (0.7 &#xb0;C)&#xa0;and time-trial performance was 39:36 (04:31) and 40:53 (05:53) minutes in the GEL and NO-GEL conditions, respectively (P = .340; 95% CI, -222 to 88&#xa0;s; d = -0.22). Sweat production increased in the GEL condition (1140 [257]&#xa0;mL) compared to the NO-GEL condition (961 [202]&#xa0;mL) (t = 2.482, P = .042; 95% CI, 08 to 349&#xa0;mL; d = 0.77).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">Menthol improved perception but increased thermoregulatory sweating and did not enhance performance (partial hypothesis support).</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Barwood</LastName><ForeName>Martin</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-1409-2191</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Faculty of Health, Wellness and Life Sciences, Leeds Trinity University, Leeds, United Kingdom.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Barwood</LastName><ForeName>Holly</ForeName><Initials>H</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Emergency Department, University Hospital of North Durham, Durham, United Kingdom.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Davis</LastName><ForeName>Danielle</ForeName><Initials>D</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0001-5440-5765</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Faculty of Health, Wellness and Lif